I think agood argument against an abort is that, unlike most man-rated rockets, the StarShip has multiple independent engines- even the R7/Soyuz family only has multiple nozzles fed from the same engine

The only really strong argument in favor is a failure of the rocket itself, such as an explosion, which would require a mechanical abort, but as the Shuttle showed, the points in a launch where an abort is 1. required and 2. possible are actually very few and far between

So long as SpaceX can continue to launch and test until explosions are no longer occurring, I would say a mechanical abort is not really required

Perhaps a safe-room style rating of the actual room occupied during a launch and landing would suffice, to protect the crew during a disaster to egress in some other way, similar to how there are plans for certain aircraft to have very heavily protected cockpits

People have to remember that in the two Shuttle losses, there would have been zero chance for the crew had there been a mechanical abort, and the solution was to upgrade the vehicle and its systems to remove the chances of such a disaster in future

StarShip's development, unlike Shuttle's, is the opposite and requires proving technology before it is human rated, when the Shuttle's first launch was crewed despite all the issues

Had SpaceX developed the Shuttle instead of StarShip, they'd have spent a year shooting foam at the wings to test integrity of the tiles

when you think about it....how can it not be on fire ?. Exhaust gasses at extremely high volumes flooding the engine compartment at 2810 Celsius at landing. The engine skirt leaves little room between it and the ground . any combustibles such as avionics and sensor network wiring would instantaneously ignite. Elons next trick is to design proper landing legs and get rid of the skirt. A heat shield would be a challenge considering the massive amount of gimbal travel the engines perform.
